<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10065b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10065b">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10065b"> 65(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Cap Nord Hammerfest / night begins 11 Nov / ends 23 Jan 74ds / day begins 16 May / 26 July 74 days</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Le journal le plus <i>septentrional</i> de notre plan&egrave;te est le journal des Esquimaux, intitul&eacute; <i>Asnagag dlintit;</i> apr&egrave;s lui, vient <i>Le Cap Nord</i>, qui para&icirc;t &agrave; Hammersfest. Les abonn&eacute;s de ce journal n&apos;ont qu&apos;un seul jour et une seule nuit par ann&eacute;e pour le lire. La nuit commence le 11 novembre et finit sans interruption, le 23 janvier, soit <i>soixante-quatorze fois vingt-quatre heures</i>! Il est vrai que les lecteurs du <i>Cap Nord</i> ont le temps de parcourir les faits divers et les annonces de leur journal, car ils ont une interminable journ&eacute;e, aussi longue que la nuit: le soleil se l&egrave;ve le 16 mai et ne se couche que le 26 juillet, soit un jour de <i>soixante-douze fois vingt-quatre heures</i>! <font color="green">[The most northern newspaper on our planet is the newspaper of the Eskimos, called the Asnagag dlintit; after that comes the Cap Nord, which appears in Hammersfest. The subscribers of this newspaper have only one day and only one night each year to read it. Night begins on November 11 and ends, without interruption, on January 23, that is to say it is 74 times 24 hours long! It is true that the readers of the Cap Nord have the time to dwell on the news items and advertisements of their paper because they have an interminable day, which is as long as their night: the sun rises on May 16 and does not set until July 26, making for a day of 72 times 24 hours!]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 267</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
